    "abstract": [],
    "body_text": [
        {
            "text": "We went through the comment by Cure et al. in rebuttal to our article entitled \"Should anti-diabetic medications be reconsidered amid COVID-19 pandemic?\" (1) Although it is interesting, certain clarifications are needed.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 31,
                    "end": 42,
                    "text": "Cure et al.",
                    "ref_id": null
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor"
        },
        {
            "text": "Firstly, the authors do agree that insulin reduces the activity of ADAM-17, metalloproteinase that cleaves ACE2 (2, 3) . This should, in turn, increase the expression of ACE2. On the contrary, Cure et al. state that ACE2 levels are reduced with insulin.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 112,
                    "end": 115,
                    "text": "(2,",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF1"
                },
                {
                    "start": 116,
                    "end": 118,
                    "text": "3)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF2"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor"
        },
        {
            "text": "This disparity needs clarification.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor"
        },
        {
            "text": "Secondly, we agree with the authors that activation of NHE by insulin can lead to intracellular alkalization and inhibit binding and entry of SARS-CoV-2. However, NHE1 activity of erythrocytes has been found to be insulin-resistant in obese subjects (4) . Interestingly, NHE1 is also predominantly expressed in lungs and might be resistant to the action of insulin in people with T2DM. Moreover, activation of NHE1 in the pulmonary arterial has been implicated in the pathogenesis of pulmonary arterial hypertension (5) . This would be undesirable in a patient with COVID-19 and acute respiratory distress syndrome.",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 250,
                    "end": 253,
                    "text": "(4)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF3"
                },
                {
                    "start": 516,
                    "end": 519,
                    "text": "(5)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF4"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor"
        },
        {
            "text": "Thirdly, the original commentary by us was intended towards people with diabetes mellitus (DM) at risk for developing COVID-19 and not towards those already diagnosed with COVID-19. However, much of the comments put forward by Cure et al. cater to people with DM already having COVID-19. As in any patient with severe infection/sepsis/hypoxia, use of metformin in COVID-19 does theoretically increase the risk of lactic acidosis (6) . Notwithstanding this fact, metformin use in patients with severe septic shock has been found to significantly lower in-hospital mortality as compared to non-users (7) .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 429,
                    "end": 432,
                    "text": "(6)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF5"
                },
                {
                    "start": 598,
                    "end": 601,
                    "text": "(7)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF6"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor"
        },
        {
            "text": "Finally, the discussion on dapagliflozin is also controversial. By inhibiting NHE, dapagliflozin should theoretically result in intracellular acidosis. Thus, activation of NHE by insulin and subsequent rise in intracellular pH will be counteracted by inhibition of NHE by dapagliflozin when both drugs are used in combination.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor"
        },
        {
            "text": "Moreover, patients on dapagliflozin will be at a higher risk of dehydration and acute kidney injury amid the already increased insensible water loss precipitated by fever and tachypnea (8) . Lastly, acute illness happens to be the most common precipitating factor for euglycemic diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) in patients on SGLT2 inhibitors (9).",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 185,
                    "end": 188,
                    "text": "(8)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF7"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor"
        },
        {
            "text": "Moreover, SARS-CoV-2, per se may aggravate pancreatic \u03b2-cell damage and precipitate DKA (10) .",
            "cite_spans": [
                {
                    "start": 88,
                    "end": 92,
                    "text": "(10)",
                    "ref_id": "BIBREF9"
                }
            ],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor"
        },
        {
            "text": "Thus, in the absence of robust data, we would be highly skeptical and advice against the use of dapagliflozin in diabetic patients with COVID-19. Insulin however remains a good choice for in-hospital patients; however, in the absence of in-clinic visits, it might be difficult to counsel diabetic patients in community about insulin usage amid the ongoing pandemic.",
            "cite_spans": [],
            "ref_spans": [],
            "section": "Dear Editor"
        }
    ],
